******
[3]
Date: Tue 26 Jul 2011
Source: goldcoast.com.au, Australian Associated Press (AAP) report
[edited]
http://www.goldcoast.com.au/article/2011/07/26/335785_gold-coast-news.html


The 1st dog to contract the Hendra virus has scientists guessing
whether the virus is being transmitted differently or if humans can
now catch the disease from canines.

The male kelpie tested positive to the virus yesterday [25 Jul 2011].
It has been taken from its owners and they'll be asked for permission
to put it down, as required under national Hendra guidelines,
Biosecurity Queensland says. The much-loved family pet lives on a
property in Mt Alford, west of the Gold Coast, where 3 horses died of
the virus in late June and early July [2011]. One of the horses is
believed to have infected the dog.

Only humans, bats, and horses have carried the virus previously.

Queensland chief vet Rick Symons said it was unclear if the leap to a
dog indicated a change in the way the virus was transmitted. "What we
are seeing here is an evolving disease, and an evolving virus, and
there are changes as the virus evolves and the exposure changes," he
told reporters in Brisbane. "We don't know in this instance (if the
virus has changed) ... all the work done to date has been that this is
a very stable virus."

Queensland's chief health officer Dr Jeannette Young said scientists
were yet to confirm if humans could contract the disease from animals
other than horses. "I don't know," she said. "We know about the risk
of horses. We don't really know the risk from other animals."

She said the dog was not excreting the virus and had a very low risk
of transmitting the disease, and humans needed to be exposed to a very
large amount of the virus to become unwell.

"I don't know about greater risk, but it is something we do need to
look at very carefully," she said. "This has changed our knowledge
quite significantly."

Two other dogs on the property have been found to be negative for the
virus so far.

Premier Anna Bligh said she'd meet with a joint Queensland-NSW Hendra
taskforce on Wednesday [27 Jul 2011].

"We need to understand better what is happening with this disease,"
she told reporters in Brisbane. "It is relatively unknown and, despite
the scientific effort to date, there are continuing developments that
I think are very worrying."

Dr Peter Reid, the vet involved in the 1st Hendra outbreak in 1994,
said proof dogs could also contract the potentially deadly Hendra
virus was a huge concern for every pet owner. "Now we know it can jump
to dogs it's a bigger fight and opens up a whole gamut of concerns,"
he said.

Scientific research has shown the virus can jump to cats, guinea pigs,
hamsters, ferrets, pigs, and dogs, but this is the 1st case of an
actual transmission in natural conditions.

Since [20 Jun 2011], 14 horses infected with Hendra have died or been
put down, 10 in Queensland and 4 in NSW.

The virus has only ever been detected in the 2 eastern Australian
states. Cases have spanned from west of Cairns, in north Queensland,
to Chinchilla on Queensland's western Darling Downs, and to Macksville
on the New South Wales mid-north coast.

More than 57 people are believed to have been exposed to
Hendra-infected horses in Queensland and NSW. All are now undergoing
tests.

