Communicated by:
ProMED-mail
<promed@promedmail.org>

[Since 1994 it seems there has been some evidence, even laboratory
transmissions, that other species were capable of supporting the
virus. Further if this kelpie is not ill, not shedding virus, then he
is presenting us with a fantastic opportunity for study. Such an
approach would allow his life to be spared and let us learn a great
deal. Perhaps there are animals that seroconvert but never become ill,
and never shed virus. This may indicate exposure but nothing else.

Further, it would seem prudent to be sure the test is validated,
especially since he was negative on the 1st 2 tests. What is different
about this test?

Has any one looked at how much virus is being shed from the saliva of
a horse? Or even the urine of the horse? It seems it would be
important to learn from the horse as well as from the dog.

Learning from this situation, vs simply euthanasia may be more
valuable in saving lives in the future. Does a dog pass virus in
saliva? Urine? Feces? These are important when it comes to having pets
in our homes, many stations have pets as well as working animals, and
some animals are both.

There really is so much to learn yet about this virus. We need to
operate in a cautious but extremely curious atmosphere to learn all we
can and solve the many unanswered questions. - Mod.TG]
